{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628305"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.15,0.19,0.19,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9902"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60484"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1311"},{"type":"tags","id":"4499"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA young obese woman has a pulsatile, daily continuous headache that is bifrontotemporal. There is orbital pain, and a cranial nerve VI palsy. She is on Vitamin A and anabolic steroids\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Ischaemic stroke"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH), previously known as pseudotumor cerebri. \u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects young obese women and is characterised by increased intracranial pressure without a space-occupying lesion. Risk factors include obesity, vitamin A derivatives, and anabolic steroids - all present in this case. The continuous nature of the headache, papilloedema, and sixth nerve palsy are characteristic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E presents with sudden onset, thunderclap headache. The absence of meningism or altered consciousness makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with sudden onset focal neurological deficits in addition to headache. The gradual onset and isolated sixth nerve palsy would be unusual for this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to IIH with headache and papilloedema. While it should be considered in the differential diagnosis, the presence of known risk factors for IIH makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with sudden onset focal neurological deficits. The presence of continuous headache, papilloedema, and an isolated sixth nerve palsy would be unusual for this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of IIH includes weight loss, discontinuation of contributing medications, and often acetazolamide. Regular ophthalmological monitoring is essential as visual loss can occur if the condition is left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension commonly presents with headache and cranial nerve VI palsy in young obese women.","Vitamin A toxicity and anabolic steroids are risk factors for idiopathic intracranial hypertension.","Daily continuous headache with orbital pain suggests increased intracranial pressure rather than acute vascular events."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374.","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146.","Wall M. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Neurol Clin. 2010 Aug;28(3):593-617. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2010.03.003. PMID: 20637991; PMCID: PMC2908600.","Wakerley BR, Mollan SP, Sinclair AJ. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension: Update on diagnosis and management. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):384-388. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0232. PMID: 32675143; PMCID: PMC7385768."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60484"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T13:10:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T13:10:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9902"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74978"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"po